hority","source":"background","provenance":null}],"resources":["**\"Your Money or Your Life\" by Vicki Robin & Joe Dominguez** – Foundational text on values-based budgeting and the concept of \"enough\"; introduces the life energy framework for evaluating expenditures.","**\"The Psychology of Money\" by Morgan Housel** – Explores behavioral dimensions of financial decision-making with well-cited research; essential for understanding why rational budgets fail behaviorally.","**Journal of Financial Planning (FPA)** – Peer-reviewed journal publishing empirical research on budgeting behavior, savings rates, and financial planning effectiveness (financialplanningassociation.org).","**NBER Working Papers on Household Finance** (nber.org) – National Bureau of Economic Research papers including landmark studies on savings behavior, debt management, and behavioral interventions in personal finance.","**\"Predictably Irrational\" by Dan Ariely** – Rigorously covers the behavioral economics principles (mental accounting, pain of paying, present bias) that explain why standard budgeting advice is resisted and how to design around those biases."]}